    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Global Warming: Costly Solutions?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Dr Paul Epstein, associate director of Center for Health and the Global Environment, Harvard Medical School, responds to Nov 13 article on global warming; comments on need for clean energy development in Central America</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U.S. Signs a Pact to Reduce Gases Tied to Global Warming'' (front page, Nov. 13): The tragedy in Central America provides an opportunity to begin a course of clean development. Emergency aid is needed, but the aid must provide a foundation for future development.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U.S. Signs a Pact to Reduce Gases Tied to Global Warming'' (front page, Nov. 13): The tragedy in Central America provides an opportunity to begin a course of clean development. Emergency aid is needed, but the aid must provide a foundation for future development.</p>
        <p>Progress throughout the Latin American isthmus based upon clean-energy sources could provide a laboratory to stimulate production and installation of nonpolluting, climate-friendly technologies. It would also underscore the causal connection between fossil fuel emissions and the violent instability of the global climate.</p>
        <p>PAUL R. EPSTEIN, M.D.  Boston, Nov. 13, 1998</p>
        <p>The writer is associate director, Center for Health and the Global Environment, Harvard Medical School.</p>
      </block>
